[3] Uganda
Date: Wed 23 May 2012
Source: Daily Monitor [edited]
http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Cholera+kills+100++more+hospitalised+/-/688334/1411510/-/view/printVersion/-/r09tf4/-/index.html

The Ministry of Health this weekend [week ending 27 May 2012] is preparing to launch a mass immunisation campaign to combat an outbreak of measles which has spread from 18 to 46 districts. As of 30 Apr 2012, data from the Health Ministry showed that about 3270 children between 4 and 14 years had been recorded as suffering from measles in 18 districts.

But Ms Nakamatte has told Daily Monitor that: "To-date, 46 districts including Kampala, Namayingo, Jinja, Busia, Bugiri, Nebbi, Sheema, Wakiso, Iganga, Luuka, Lwengo, Masaka, Mayuge, Buikwe, Mityana, Koboko, Mitooma, Mbale, Bukomansimbi, Bukwo, Butaleja, Buvuma, Gulu, Kalungu, Kiryandongo, Kole, Mbarara, Namutumba, Rakai, Sironko, Buliisa, Buyende, Kalagala, Kamuli, Kanungu, Kiruhura, Luweero, Yumbe, Nakaseke, Ibanda, Kibaale, Kayunga, Bushenyi, Kyankwanzi, Budaka and Mukono have surpassed the measles epidemic threshold. We have not confirmed any deaths, but our data show an increase in new cases, with 630 measles cases recorded in May 2012 alone," she said.

The Ministry of Health says at least 42 per cent of measles cases are not vaccinated, with nearly all suspect cases in children below 9 months not vaccinated for measles, which has prompted an additional nationwide mass measles campaign that will be conducted from 26-28 May [2012].

Ms Catherine Ntabadde, the Uganda Red Cross Society spokesperson, said the exercise would target more than one million children in 14 districts that have been identified as the most affected by both polio and measles. These include Kampala, Hoima, Nebbi, Pallisa, Tororo, Jinja, Mbarara, among others.

[Byline: Agatha Ayebazibwe]

