[7] Argentina (Buenos Aires)
Date: Sat 26 May 2012
Source: Diario de Cuyo [In Spanish, machine trans, edited]
http://www.diariodecuyo.com.ar/home/new_noticia.php?noticia_id=520602


Measles outbreak alert issued by Ministry of Health
------------------------------
The Ministry of Health issued an alert yesterday concerning detection of a possible case of measles that affects one woman in the city of Buenos Aires who had traveled to Europe and returned with symptoms of the disease. So far no indigenous cases have been recorded in the Argentina since 2000.

The Health Minister said in a statement that the national alert system was alerted on Thursday night and said the suspected case is now the focus of efforts to contain the disease. The woman, 35, has no record of vaccination against measles, said the Ministry. She had traveled to Europe in the last 4 weeks and re-entered the country with symptoms consistent with the disease.

He explained that as in Argentina had not recorded indigenous measles virus circulation for 12 years, and consequently the emergence of a single case is considered an outbreak. Control measures against measles involve the reporting of cases to health authorities, adult and child isolation, and strict compliance with respiratory isolation in hospitals. Carla Vizzotti, the head of the National Vaccine-Preventable Diseases Control at the Ministry of Health, said the risk of introduction of this disease into our country is high as measles virus is currently circulating widely in Europe, South-east Asia, the eastern Pacific and Africa. '

In the Americas, however, the disease is in the process of elimination, the specialist reported. The last cases of measles were detected in the country last August [2011] when 2 people who had traveled to South Africa contracted the disease and infected their families on return to the country.

